Report cron session, which kicked off at 18:15 UTC and is still active, though it's spawned a few child sessions that have already finished. And then there's a direct message to Telegram from master-orchestrator that's been running for a while now. Telegram direct to Lead): status=done (ended ~18:22 UTC, ~2h9m ago)\\n\\n6. **`agent:master-orchestrator:main`** - \\\"main\\\" (heartbeat) - status=done (ended ~19:41 UTC, ~50m ago)\\n\\n7. **`agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5163901258`** - \\\"QLHV group\\\" - running (updatedAt 1776191432025 = 18:23 UTC), started at 1776163408296. Duration: 1776198729 - 1776163408 = 35321s = ~9h49m. Status: running.\\n\\nThe main session shows as running but ended around 19:41 UTC based on the heartbeat messages, and it's also listed as done in the status field.\\n\\nSo filtering for only running master-orchestrator sessions, I'm seeing the cron session for e7885813, another cron for 6f3323ef, the QLHV cron, and the Telegram direct session all marked as running. The cron:ed2d0b5d session started about 2h47m ago, while cron:e7885813 is this current cron session itself.\\n\\nLooking at the remaining sessions, cron:e7885813 just started seconds ago, cron:6f3323ef is the DTLX 5p monitor that's been running for roughly 2h47m, the QLHV 5p monitor started about 56m ago, the Telegram direct session ended about 2h9m ago so it's no longer active, and the QLHV group session has been running for nearly 10 hours.\\n\\nI'm realizing I need to recalculate the durations more carefully—the Telegram direct session is actually done, so I should focus on just the four active cron sessions and exclude this current cron session itself.\\n\\nLooking at the QLHV group session, it shows as running but ended at 1776163783190, which converts to around 18:09 UTC, yet the updatedAt timestamp is from 18:23 UTC—there's a discrepancy I need to resolve.\\n\\nActually, the runtimeMs of 8014ms (8 seconds) confirms it ran briefly around 18:09-18:16 UTC and then