{"type":"message","id":"f3864af6","parentId":"f3cc703e","timestamp":"2026-04-14T20:35:59.697Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The memory retrieval failed (disabled: true, error: \"path required\"). Let me try to read the heartbeat-state.json file directly.\n\nNow let me analyze the current state from sessions_list:\n\nCurrent time: 20:34 UTC 14 Apr\n\nRunning sessions (master-orchestrator agent, status=running):\n1. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7` - This is THIS cron session\n2. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` - running, updatedAt 1776198729176 (~20:32 UTC), started at 1776198728659 (~20:32 UTC)\n\n\n3. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` - running, updatedAt 1776198642636 (~20:30 UTC), started at 1776188636412\n4. `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5163901258` - running, updatedAt 1776191432025 (~18:30 UTC), started at 1776163408296\n\nThe main orchestrator session and telegram:direct:6053576134 are both done, and I'm filtering out child sessions spawned by the cron.\n\nLooking back at the previous cycle's state at 20:31 UTC, the active sessions were the DTLX 5p Monitor, QLHV 5p Monitor, Agent Status to Lead cron, and the QLHV group telegram session—all still running.\n\nNow comparing that baseline to the current 20:34 UTC snapshot, I notice the QLHV 5p Monitor has dropped off the list, which is the notable change. The other three sessions remain active. the previous cycle at 20:31 UTC, the `cron:ed2d0b5d` was listed as running. Let me check if it ended.\n\nLooking at the session list, I don't see `cron:ed2d0b5d` in the running sessions. The sessions I can see that are running:\n1. `cron:ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7` - THIS session\n2. `cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` - running\n3. `cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` - running\n4. `telegram:group:-5163901258` - running\n\nI'm not finding `cron:ed2d0b5d` as a separate running session in the list, which means it must have ended. The previous 20:31 UTC report had it running for about 56 minutes, so it likely terminated between then and now.\n\nLooking more carefully at the session keys, I notice `cron:ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7` is actually a child session spawned by the master orchestrator's main cron, not the QLHV 5p Monitor cron itself. The 5p monitor cron would have a different session key structure. I'm parsing through the session keys more carefully now—the direct message session shows as done from 18:22 UTC, but the cron:e7885813 session has been running for over 3 hours since 17:17 UTC, so those are distinct sessions. The previous report at 20:31 UTC mentioned four sessions, and I'm cross-referencing those with the current session data to identify what's actually changed. The `cron:ed2d0b5d` session must have ended between the last report at 20:31 UTC and now at 20:34 UTC, which is the only state change to track. I'm confirming that `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` is the same Agent Status to Lead cron session that was reported at 20:31 UTC, now running for about 3h14m total. I'm checking the heartbeat-state.json file to see if there's a stored baseline from the last cycle, but it looks like the memory retrieval failed with a path error, so I'll need to read it directly from the workspace instead. Let me compile the changes I've detected so far.\n\nThe `cron:ed2d0b5d` QLHV 5p Monitor session has ended, which is the only real state change I'm seeing. The main session and telegram direct session are both done as expected, so I should check the heartbeat-state.json file directly to see if there's additional context about the previous state before finalizing this report.","thinkingSignature":"4a46f8c832cebb2c199ed900ad8d742551108a86992f27c2ecb6e19d655aa2ee"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cnwtpvsramh6_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":